00:01.400 --> 00:12.680
Is this taping now? The tape is now on. Anything you say now will be recorded.
Mr. Simak, could you give us your background, where you grew up, how you spent

00:12.680 --> 00:28.800
your time as a young boy? I was born on my grandfather's farm, which stood on
the high hills above the confluence of the Mississippi and Wisconsin River. And

00:28.800 --> 00:34.780
I grew up as a farm boy. I went to a rural high school.

00:37.460 --> 00:48.500
We lived and went about to the tail end of the pioneer period. Most of us are.
My family is poor, and all of our neighbors were poor. We didn't think we were

00:48.500 --> 00:53.540
poor, but we were. We didn't think so because everybody was in the same shape.

00:56.540 --> 01:02.880
And I did go to, after high

01:02.880 --> 01:14.100
school, I attended the teacher's training course and taught school for a short
time. And then went to the University of Wisconsin at Madison, but I did not

01:14.100 --> 01:23.620
finish there. I ran out of money. I got a job in the newspaper, and I've been in
the newspaper business ever since until six, seven years ago.

01:26.600 --> 01:31.360
Okay. How did you decide to become a newspaper man?

01:34.840 --> 01:39.100
I think there was no decision because I think I always knew what I wanted to
write.

01:42.200 --> 01:55.160
And I never really thought of writing fiction or writing books or anything of
that sort. It seemed to me that the way to write was to be a newspaper man. My

01:55.160 --> 02:02.420
mother, who was a very well-educated woman, had books in the house all the time,
and I read them.

02:10.460 --> 02:22.060
And she used to sit at the table by the light of a kerosene lamp and read it
each evening after all the work was done. And I asked her at one time, I

02:22.060 --> 02:36.000
remember, if a newspaper carried all the news, printed all the news that was.
And she, in the manner of that day, and because people were not as cynical then

02:36.000 --> 02:48.500
as they are now, said, yes, that's true. And I asked her another question that I
thought was important. I said, is all the news true? Is what the newspaper

02:48.500 --> 02:59.740
writes true? And again, with that lack of cynicism and faith that the people of
that time had, she said, yes, it was. And that decided me, decided me to be,

02:59.820 --> 03:10.180
want to be a newspaper man. How long were you in the newspaper business before
you wrote your first science fiction stories? No, wait, that's going to take

03:10.180 --> 03:10.320
some.

03:13.560 --> 03:32.220
I started my newspaper career in 1929. And my first short story appeared in, I
think, 1931. And I wrote, at that time I wrote several other short stories which

03:32.220 --> 03:45.260
were published. And at about that time the magazine, all magazines, the science
fiction magazines and all others, ran into hard times because the Great

03:45.260 --> 03:59.320
Depression came along. And so I, there was no market, practically no market. So
I dropped out and didn't do any more writing, any other fiction writing of any

03:59.320 --> 04:14.060
kind until I think it was 37 or 38. And I started writing again because the
magazines had come back. John Campbell had been named editor of Astounding. And I

04:14.060 --> 04:31.200
felt very sure that I could sell my work to John Campbell. So I started in again.
And I think since, since 1938, 1939, I think it's 38, 37 or 38. There was only

04:31.200 --> 04:42.200
one year in which none of my work appeared. There was one year that's blank. And
I can't remember which year that it was. And I have no idea why that occurred.

04:44.980 --> 05:02.380
When you began writing fiction, what influenced you to write science fiction?
Well, because when I was a boy, I had read, Jules Verne and, and I think H.G.

05:02.540 --> 05:10.780
Wells, although I don't actually remember any H.G. Wells works, but I must have
read them, Edgar Allan Poe and Haggard.

05:13.060 --> 05:25.940
And I thought what a wonderful thing that was. I just had an awful interest in
the field. I wanted to read it myself and I found out when I decided that I

05:25.940 --> 05:37.500
wanted to write. When I found out the newspaper didn't give me everything that I
wanted in the writing field. I decided that on the part that on my spare time I

05:37.500 --> 05:50.140
write, I naturally seemed to turn to science fiction. Because it was something I
was acquainted with. I felt very sure that I could do the job of it. And I was

05:50.140 --> 05:58.260
quite fortunate, of course, because there was no competition at that time. If
you could string three sentences together and make a paragraph, somebody would

05:58.260 --> 05:58.840
buy the story.

06:02.740 --> 06:17.620
Did you have any interest in science when you were growing up? Some interest.
You must realize that at that time, science was a somewhat different thing than

06:17.620 --> 06:29.500
it is today. Today, science is something that a good many people are interested
in. There are a great many engineers and a great many technicians and just

06:29.500 --> 06:40.940
ordinary lay people who are interested in science. At that time, science was a
rather elevated situation, elevated crap. There were a few great scientists.

06:41.600 --> 06:49.320
There were a few engineers. But mostly those were either mining engineers or
civil engineers.

06:52.060 --> 07:08.940
There have been very old science, very old pride at that time. And the public
interest in it was fairly low. I was taken by them. I used to read, I forget

07:08.940 --> 07:19.940
what old magazine it was. It was a magazine. Would it be Scientific American?
Would it go back that far? I think so. I used to read Scientific American, which

07:19.940 --> 07:30.580
had some marvelous articles in it, particularly on astronomy. I didn't
understand any of it, or understood very little of it. But the mystery and the

07:30.580 --> 07:42.780
wonder of it caught me by the smoke. And that was the sort of interest I had at
that time in it. I don't think very many people had interest in science the way

07:42.780 --> 07:45.660
that they can be said to have interest in science today.

07:48.560 --> 07:57.420
You mentioned when you resumed your writing in 1938 when the magazines had
recovered that you thought you could write for John Campbell. What was in your

07:57.420 --> 08:02.760
writing that you thought would appeal to Campbell? I've read a lot of John
Campbell's work.

08:07.920 --> 08:16.360
I knew that John Campbell was favored

08:16.360 --> 08:27.280
what we today call hard science fiction. And I thought that I could write that
kind of science fiction. I did write what amounted to hard science fiction for

08:27.280 --> 08:37.220
some years, and then began to turn over to the softer science fiction such as
most of which... Well, most people write soft science fiction today. Only a few

08:37.220 --> 08:42.060
of the old hands and maybe a few new beginners write the hard science fiction
today.

08:46.360 --> 08:56.940
Some people feel that John Campbell influenced science fiction positively.
Others feel that he influenced it very negatively. What's your assessment of his

08:56.940 --> 09:08.380
influence on the field? I think John Campbell probably made science fiction what
it is. He was the one man who stood there and fought for science fiction and

09:08.380 --> 09:10.720
directed science fiction.

09:11.860 --> 09:16.700
You can't take away from John Campbell anything good that has been said of him.

09:17.820 --> 09:24.840
In later years we became rather hype bound with his opinion and a little big tutorial.

09:26.640 --> 09:31.820
And he was a good influence to start with. I think that probably you can see was a bad

09:31.820 --> 09:42.440
influence. But he lost his prestige as a great science fiction editor. I suppose quite a few years

09:42.440 --> 09:48.900
before he died. There were some of the boys that were writing science fiction friends of

09:48.900 --> 09:55.500
mine that posted that they could tell the science fiction story to Campbell anytime they wanted

09:55.500 --> 10:02.620
because they knew exactly what buttons to push. And if they pushed the right button they knew

10:02.620 --> 10:05.500
they'd jamboree the story. He was that predictable.

10:10.460 --> 10:17.940
You stuck to short stories during your early years. Was this because you were full time

10:17.940 --> 10:19.500
employed as a newspaper man?

10:19.500 --> 10:30.560
Well not necessarily but a short story is the training ground for the novelist. You can

10:30.560 --> 10:38.140
learn a lot more from writing a short story than you can writing a novel. It's shorter

10:38.140 --> 10:46.060
to write, somewhat easier to write. You don't have the time invested in a short story to

10:46.060 --> 10:54.660
write a novel. If you spend as a beginner probably six months or a year writing a novel

10:54.660 --> 11:01.060
and it fails when that's catastrophic. But during that same time you could write perhaps

11:01.640 --> 11:16.040
a dozen short stories and if only one of them sold why okay you have made a beginning. So
it's the path that most people take to becoming writers.

11:16.040 --> 11:24.900
And that doesn't apply only to the science fiction field but

11:24.900 --> 11:26.500
to any literature.

11:29.640 --> 11:39.820
According to my information in 1944 the first two stories from City appeared. This seemed

11:39.820 --> 11:43.820
like quite a leap from what I should have written in that it has the dogs and the robots and

11:43.820 --> 11:49.120
the men. Could you give us a little bit of background on how you conceived the ideas and put them together

11:49.120 --> 11:49.900
for that series?

11:53.880 --> 12:05.080
It wasn't weak because I always regard the city stories as a sort of watershed in my writing. I have been

12:05.820 --> 12:19.600
writing the early type of science fiction work up until then. And it seemed to me that something

12:19.600 --> 12:28.000
better could be done than was being done. Strangely enough, at about the same time a number of other

12:28.000 --> 12:36.680
people seemed to think the same thing. There's no accounting for something like that happening.

12:39.700 --> 12:57.980
I think it was my disillusioned by the war that made me write the City series. It's a

12:59.740 --> 13:13.180
terrible period in history. Much of human dignity has been shared away. It was not the kind of world that we had lived in

13:13.180 --> 13:23.040
up until that time. I was far myself wanting to retreat from it. So I retreated from it in my

13:23.040 --> 13:31.920
own mental way by going into another dimension, into another world, creating a sort of a fantasy

13:31.920 --> 13:44.620
of myself as it turned out others also were able to find some refuge. I think if the City series

13:44.620 --> 13:51.620
was written today that they probably would not get the attention that they got back in the early 40s.

13:53.980 --> 14:02.880
I wrote them exactly the right type of stories, exactly the right type. Without knowing I was doing it.

14:06.580 --> 14:12.600
